{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a3242bbd-ac94-47ee-82d6-c1068fbfdf6c","content":"## What happened\n\n**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS** because Apple's native cryptographic framework (Security.framework / CryptoKit) does not support DSA, and .NET 11 removed the compatibility shim that was previously keeping it alive.\n\nThis has been a long-anticipated removal. Microsoft has been progressively dropping built-in support for algorithms that the underlying OS doesn't natively provide, and DSA has been on the deprecation path for several .NET releases. On macOS, there is no native provider for DSA — unlike Windows (CNG) and Linux (OpenSSL), which still have one.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep verifying DSA signatures)\n\nReplace the built-in `DSA` class with the managed **BouncyCastle** implementation, which runs everywhere without OS dependencies:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\"); // match your hash\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is pure managed code — it works on Linux, Windows, and macOS with no native dependency.\n\n### Option 2 — Migrate away from DSA entirely\n\nIf you control the signing side, **migrate to ECDSA or Ed25519**, which are supported natively on all three platforms:\n\n```csharp\nusing var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);\nbool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);\n```\n\nThis is the longer-term correct answer — DSA is a legacy algorithm and will continue losing platform support.\n\n### What NOT to do\n\nDon't try to bundle OpenSSL on macOS yourself or P/Invoke into it — that creates a maintenance and security burden that BouncyCastle avoids entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dc538c0a-f544-438e-99f3-7b7a4ae33446","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me provide what I know about this.\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA` class on macOS historically used the Apple Security framework (SecKeychain-based APIs). However, Apple has been deprecating older cryptographic APIs, and .NET has been gradually dropping support for algorithms that the underlying OS no longer supports well.\n\nStarting with .NET 7, Microsoft began throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` for certain cryptographic operations on macOS. Specifically, DSA was never supported by Apple's CryptoKit/Security framework in a modern way - .NET on macOS used OpenSSL for DSA operations initially, then in some versions it was handled differently.\n\n\nThe issue is that `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple doesn't provide native DSA support in their modern crypto frameworks, and .NET stopped relying on OpenSSL for these operations on macOS. Since the user says it worked on .NET 10 but broke on .NET 11, this suggests a change in how .NET 11 handles DSA on macOS, likely removing a compatibility layer that was previously in place. deprecated DSA support in newer .NET versions. Since I don't have specific knowledge about .NET 11 changes, I'm reasoning from what I know: Microsoft has been systematically removing support for legacy crypto algorithms on platforms where the OS doesn't natively support them, and macOS doesn't provide modern DSA support, so it's likely DSA remains unsupported or was removed entirely in .NET 11.\n\nThe practical solutions would be using BouncyCastle for managed DSA implementation, leveraging OpenSSL through P/Invoke on macOS, or migrating to ECDSA or RSA signatures instead. 2. How to fix it (BouncyCastle for managed DSA, or migrate away from DSA)","outputTokens":1804,"requestId":"4009:126516:13AE9FA:1663AC3:69F94B29"},"id":"6e03a200-3e24-48a5-aa59-2059d4b058c3","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:43:44.674Z","parentId":"eeb969b1-ed51-40d9-8049-c7536c0b16ad"}
